VALUES
(42, 10, 8, 42, 9, 48, 48, 'receive you', 'Receiving and Greatness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the act of receiving, linking hospitality to spiritual significance. In Luke 10:8, receiving food symbolizes acceptance, while in Luke 9:48, receiving a child reflects receiving Jesus and the greatness of humility.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 8, 42, 10, 10, 10, 'whatsoever city ye enter', 'Instructions for City Reception', 'Both passages emphasize the response to city reception. The first instructs to eat what is set before you if received, while the second directs to leave if not received.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 8, 43, 13, 20, 20, 'receive you', 'Reception and Sending Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of receiving and sending. Both passages emphasize the importance of accepting those sent by Jesus, linking hospitality to the acceptance of divine authority.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 9, 40, 3, 2, 2, 'the kingdom of God is come nigh unto you', 'Kingdom of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the imminent arrival of the kingdom, with Luke stating it is ''come nigh'' and Matthew declaring it is ''at hand.'' This connection highlights a shared theme of urgency in the message of the kingdom.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 9, 43, 3, 5, 5, 'the kingdom of God is come nigh unto you', 'Connection of Kingdom of God', 'This connection highlights the theme of the kingdom of God being accessible through healing and spiritual rebirth. Both passages emphasize the necessity of transformation—whether through healing or being born of water and Spirit—to enter the kingdom of God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 9, 40, 10, 7, 8, 'The kingdom of God is come nigh unto you', 'Connection of Kingdom Messages', 'Both passages emphasize the nearness of the kingdom, with Luke stating, ''The kingdom of God is come nigh unto you,'' and Matthew declaring, ''The kingdom of heaven is at hand.'' This connection highlights the urgency of the message and the call to heal as part of the proclamation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 9, 42, 10, 11, 11, 'the kingdom of God is come nigh unto you', 'Connection of Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize that ''the kingdom of God is come nigh unto you.'' This repetition underscores the urgency and significance of the message being delivered to the cities.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 9, 42, 17, 20, 21, 'The kingdom of God is come nigh unto you', 'Connection of the Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize the nature of the kingdom of God. In Luke 10:9, it is proclaimed as near, while in Luke 17:20-21, it is described as within individuals, highlighting its spiritual presence rather than a physical manifestation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 9, 44, 28, 7, 10, 'The kingdom of God is come nigh unto you', 'Healing and the Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize the act of healing as a sign of the kingdom of God being present. In Luke, Jesus instructs to heal the sick and proclaim the kingdom, while in Acts, Paul heals the sick, demonstrating the kingdom''s arrival through miraculous works.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 9, 41, 6, 13, 13, 'The kingdom of God is come nigh unto you', 'Healing and the Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize the act of healing the sick as a demonstration of the kingdom of God’s presence. The healing in Luke is directly linked to proclaiming that ''the kingdom of God is come nigh unto you,'' while Mark describes the healing acts performed by the disciples.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 10, 44, 18, 6, 6, 'receive you not', 'Rejection and Response to Opposition', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection in both passages. In Luke 10:10, the instruction to leave a city that does not receive the messengers parallels Paul''s response in Acts 18:6, where he declares he will turn to the Gentiles after facing opposition.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 10, 40, 10, 14, 14, 'receive you not', 'Instructions for Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of departing from a city or house that does not receive the messenger. They instruct the disciples to take a physical action, symbolizing the rejection of their message.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 10, 44, 13, 51, 51, NULL, 'Dust Shaking as Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of shaking off dust as a response to rejection. In Luke, Jesus instructs his followers to shake off the dust when not received, and in Acts, Paul and Barnabas perform this action against those who reject their message.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 10, 42, 9, 5, 5, 'receive you not', 'Rejection and Response in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the response to rejection in ministry. They instruct the disciples on how to handle cities that do not receive them, highlighting the act of shaking off dust as a testimony.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 11, 42, 10, 9, 9, 'the kingdom of God is come nigh unto you', 'Connection of Kingdom of God', 'Both passages emphasize that ''the kingdom of God is come nigh unto you.'' This connection highlights the urgency and proximity of God''s kingdom as proclaimed by Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 11, 44, 13, 51, 51, 'the very dust of your city', 'Dust Shaking Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of shaking off dust as a sign of rejection. This connection highlights the response to those who do not receive the message of the kingdom.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 11, 5, 30, 11, 14, 'the kingdom of God is come nigh unto you', 'Proximity of God''s Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s nearness in both passages. Luke emphasizes that the kingdom of God is ''come nigh unto you,'' while Deuteronomy states that the commandment is ''very nigh unto thee.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 11, 40, 10, 14, 14, NULL, 'Dust Shaking Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of shaking off dust as a sign of rejection. This connection highlights the seriousness of the response to those who do not receive the message of the kingdom of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 11, 41, 6, 11, 11, 'the very dust of your city', 'Dust as a Symbol of Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the act of shaking off dust as a symbolic gesture of judgment against those who reject the message of the kingdom of God. This connection highlights the seriousness of rejecting the gospel and the impending consequences for such actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 11, 44, 13, 26, 26, 'the kingdom of God is come nigh unto you', 'Connection of Salvation Message', 'This connection highlights the proclamation of the kingdom of God and the message of salvation. Both passages emphasize the invitation to receive God''s word, addressing those who are receptive to it.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 11, 45, 10, 8, 8, 'the kingdom of God is come nigh unto you', 'Proximity of the Kingdom of God', 'This connection highlights the theme of the kingdom of God being near. Both passages emphasize the immediacy of God''s presence and message to the people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 12, 40, 10, 15, 15, NULL, 'Judgment Comparison with Sodom', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that it shall be more tolerable for Sodom in the day of judgment than for certain cities. This connection highlights a theme of divine judgment and accountability for rejection of the message.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 12, 40, 11, 24, 24, NULL, 'Connection of Sodom''s Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the comparison of judgment for Sodom and the cities being addressed. They highlight that it will be more tolerable for Sodom in the day of judgment than for the cities rejecting Jesus'' message.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 12, 25, 4, 6, 6, 'more tolerable in that day for Sodom', 'Punishment Comparison of Sodom', 'This connection highlights the comparative severity of punishment. Both passages emphasize the fate of Sodom in relation to the punishment of God''s people.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 12, 41, 6, 11, 11, NULL, 'Judgment Comparison with Sodom', 'Both passages emphasize the severity of judgment for cities that reject the messengers. They highlight that it will be more tolerable for Sodom than for those cities that do not receive the message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 12, 26, 16, 48, 50, 'more tolerable in that day for Sodom', 'Judgment of Sodom Comparison', 'Both passages emphasize the judgment of Sodom, highlighting its iniquities. Luke 10:12 suggests that certain cities will face harsher judgment than Sodom, while Ezekiel 16:48-50 details Sodom''s sins, including pride and neglect of the needy.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 13, 23, 23, 1, 18, 'Tyre and Sidon', 'Judgment on Cities of Trade', 'Both passages emphasize the judgment against cities known for their commerce and pride. Luke 10:13 mentions Tyre and Sidon in the context of unrepentant cities, while Isaiah 23 details the destruction of Tyre and Zidon, highlighting their downfall.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 13, 26, 26, 1, 26, NULL, 'Judgment on Cities of Sin', 'Both passages emphasize the impending judgment on cities that have turned away from God. Luke 10:13 warns Chorazin and Bethsaida of their unrepentance, while Ezekiel 26:1-26 proclaims destruction upon Tyre for its arrogance against Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 13, 29, 3, 4, 8, 'if the mighty works had been done in Tyre and Sidon', 'Judgment on Tyre and Sidon', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against Tyre and Sidon in both passages. Luke 10:13 references the unrepentant cities of Chorazin and Bethsaida, suggesting that Tyre and Sidon would have repented if they had witnessed similar miracles, paralleling Joel 3:4-8''s condemnation of Tyre and Sidon for their wrongdoings.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 10, 13, 40, 11, 20, 23, 'woe unto thee, Chorazin! woe unto thee, Bethsaida!', 'Condemnation of Unrepentant Cities', 'Both passages emphasize the woe pronounced on Chorazin and Bethsaida for their lack of repentance despite witnessing mighty works. This connection highlights the comparison to Tyre and Sidon, illustrating the severity of judgment for those who reject divine revelation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
